You've got some guts, kid.

259
00:20:23,309 --> 00:20:25,478
You can stare at me all you want,

260
00:20:25,478 --> 00:20:27,654
but I'm not going to apologize.

261
00:20:28,430 --> 00:20:30,357
I'm sorry, sir,

262
00:20:31,291 --> 00:20:32,918
but you need to leave.

263
00:20:32,918 --> 00:20:35,754
You're making the other guests uncomfortable.

264
00:20:35,754 --> 00:20:38,223
Well, I've lost my appetite now.

265
00:20:39,091 --> 00:20:41,226
That's all on you, Mr. Waiter.

266
00:20:57,693 --> 00:21:01,155
I'm sorry about how I acted
in front of that customer.

267
00:21:01,155 --> 00:21:03,073
I'm sorry, sir.

268
00:21:03,073 --> 00:21:04,616
Don't worry.

269
00:21:04,616 --> 00:21:06,201
I'm sorry that it happened.

270
00:21:06,201 --> 00:21:08,203
It's okay.

271
00:21:08,203 --> 00:21:09,663
You.

272
00:21:09,663 --> 00:21:11,464
You'll start tomorrow.

273
00:21:12,141 --> 00:21:13,817
Yes, sir.

274
00:21:15,335 --> 00:21:16,970
Here you go.

275
00:21:20,799 --> 00:21:22,801
You did well today.

276
00:21:22,801 --> 00:21:24,727
Thank you, sir.

277
00:21:43,822 --> 00:21:45,449
That must be it.

278
00:21:45,449 --> 00:21:47,292
I'm telling you!

279
00:21:48,035 --> 00:21:49,711
What do you mean?

280
00:21:51,622 --> 00:21:53,332
What are you saying?

281
00:21:53,332 --> 00:21:55,042
He came to your rescue.

282
00:21:55,042 --> 00:21:56,710
He wanted brownie points.

283
00:21:56,710 --> 00:21:58,670
Don't be ridiculous.

284
00:21:58,670 --> 00:22:00,589
Well, look at you!

285
00:22:00,589 --> 00:22:03,717
You were pretty much forever alone in Korea.

286
00:22:03,717 --> 00:22:06,512
But look at what you've achieved
as soon as you came to Japan.

287
00:22:06,512 --> 00:22:08,722
Come on, I was never forever alone.

288
00:22:08,722 --> 00:22:12,184
I mean, have you ever dated anyone
who was half-decent?

289
00:22:12,184 --> 00:22:14,937
One ghosted you,
and one went to the army.

290
00:22:14,937 --> 00:22:17,356
When did you ever snag a catch?

291
00:22:17,356 --> 00:22:19,875
Then there's Min Jun, who's actually not that bad.

292
00:22:19,875 --> 00:22:22,468
But you insist he's just a friend.

293
00:22:23,696 --> 00:22:24,947
Listen.

294
00:22:24,947 --> 00:22:28,659
How many times must I tell you?
He really is just a friend.

295
00:22:28,659 --> 00:22:30,703
Sure, whatever.

296
00:22:30,703 --> 00:22:34,415
Did he cry when you left Korea?

297
00:22:34,415 --> 00:22:36,417
Poor Min Jun.

298
00:22:36,417 --> 00:22:40,254
Trust me. I bet he can't stand
being put in the friend zone.

299
00:22:40,254 --> 00:22:43,765
That's enough.
It's not like you're doing any better.

300
00:22:44,425 --> 00:22:46,218
I feel bad for your knight in shining armor.

301
00:22:46,218 --> 00:22:48,011
Doesn't he need money for school?

302
00:22:48,011 --> 00:22:51,948
I think he got a job
at a food truck across the street.

303
00:22:51,948 --> 00:22:53,100
Which is a relief.

304
00:22:53,100 --> 00:22:54,817
A food truck?

305
00:22:58,105 --> 00:22:59,823
Here you go.

306
00:23:29,011 --> 00:23:31,980
[CLOSED]

307
00:23:38,062 --> 00:23:40,947
Sorry for the wait. Thank you for coming!

308
00:23:43,567 --> 00:23:45,277
Thank you.

309
00:23:45,277 --> 00:23:46,953
What can I get you?

310
00:23:49,406 --> 00:23:52,493
You're staring at the food truck again.

311
00:23:52,493 --> 00:23:53,660
What?

312
00:23:53,660 --> 00:23:55,287
Who, me?

313
00:23:55,287 --> 00:23:57,581
No, I wasn't.

314
00:23:57,581 --> 00:23:59,458
I was just...

315
00:23:59,458 --> 00:24:02,969
checking to see if it was raining outside.

316
00:24:05,589 --> 00:24:07,591
Hong.

317
00:24:07,591 --> 00:24:11,144
- Yes, sir?
- Can you get some hotdogs for us?

318
00:24:14,264 --> 00:24:15,940
Yes, sir.

319
00:24:21,563 --> 00:24:23,148
- Thank you for your waiting!
- Here we go!

320
00:24:23,148 --> 00:24:24,733
Hong finally passes the halfway line

321
00:24:24,733 --> 00:24:27,361
and runs straight into the opponent's territory!

322
00:24:27,361 --> 00:24:28,946
Here's the moment we've all been waiting for.

323
00:24:28,946 --> 00:24:31,115
Will Hong finally get to score her first goal?

324
00:24:31,115 --> 00:24:32,783
The suspense is real!

325
00:24:32,783 --> 00:24:34,993
Now, we've got to ask!

326
00:24:34,993 --> 00:24:39,081
Did she really have to go out
with that headwrap on her head?

327
00:24:39,081 --> 00:24:40,791
What a terrible oversight!

328
00:24:40,791 --> 00:24:44,628
She's not as level-headed as she usually is.

329
00:24:44,628 --> 00:24:46,839
She must be feeling nervous.

330
00:24:46,839 --> 00:24:48,924
Perhaps she's not used to playing such games.

331
00:24:48,924 --> 00:24:51,510
Right, that must be it.

332
00:24:51,510 --> 00:24:54,229
Thank you. Please come again.

333
00:24:59,393 --> 00:25:01,186
Hello.

334
00:25:01,186 --> 00:25:02,862
Hello.

335
00:25:04,039 --> 00:25:06,048
It's been a while.

336
00:25:10,362 --> 00:25:12,656
Are you here for some hotdogs?

337
00:25:12,656 --> 00:25:14,283
Oh, yes.

338
00:25:14,283 --> 00:25:16,759
Can I have five cheese hotdogs, please?

339
00:25:16,759 --> 00:25:17,787
- Five?
- Yes, please.

340
00:25:17,787 --> 00:25:19,505
Five cheese hotdogs.

341
00:25:26,420 --> 00:25:30,181
That headwrap looks good on you.

342
00:25:31,091 --> 00:25:33,184
Thank you.

343
00:25:33,927 --> 00:25:35,262
And you, too.

344
00:25:35,262 --> 00:25:37,522
You look good in your apron.

345
00:25:39,475 --> 00:25:41,442
Thank you.

346
00:25:43,479 --> 00:25:45,488
Thank you very much.

347
00:25:47,358 --> 00:25:48,942
Here she comes!

348
00:25:48,942 --> 00:25:50,702
Get back to work!

349
00:25:52,029 --> 00:25:53,489
Come get your hotdogs!

350
00:25:53,489 --> 00:25:55,540
- Great.
- Thanks.

351
00:25:57,201 --> 00:25:58,835
Here you go.

352
00:26:00,329 --> 00:26:01,914
- Thanks.
- Here you go.

353
00:26:01,914 --> 00:26:04,083
Oh, I almost forgot.

354
00:26:04,083 --> 00:26:08,420
It's our turn to clean
the shopping district this week.

355
00:26:08,420 --> 00:26:10,714
We've always had the newbies do it.

356
00:26:10,714 --> 00:26:12,591
So, you'll be doing that from now.

357
00:26:12,591 --> 00:26:15,317
It's at 10 a.m. tomorrow.
Do you think you can do it?

358
00:26:15,317 --> 00:26:18,030
Of course. Leave it to me.

359
00:26:18,847 --> 00:26:20,391
Good luck!

360
00:26:20,391 --> 00:26:22,066
Yes, sir!

361
00:26:26,647 --> 00:26:31,318
The stores of the Kichijoji Prosperity Association

362
00:26:31,318 --> 00:26:34,446
work hard to keep the shopping district clean.

363
00:26:34,446 --> 00:26:38,909
We meet every morning
to clean up an area of the district.

364
00:26:38,909 --> 00:26:41,328
We appreciate your cooperation.

365
00:26:41,328 --> 00:26:42,955
- Thank you very much.
- Thank you very much.

366
00:26:42,955 --> 00:26:45,222
Let's start by taking attendance.

367
00:26:45,222 --> 00:26:46,682
Ichiro's Ramen?

368
00:26:46,682 --> 00:26:48,210
- Here.
- Thank you.

369
00:26:48,210 --> 00:26:49,420
Murakami Bookstore?

370
00:26:49,420 --> 00:26:51,547
- Here.
- Great.

371
00:26:51,547 --> 00:26:53,882
Inubushi's Food Truck?

372
00:26:53,882 --> 00:26:56,051
Inubushi's Food Truck?

373
00:26:56,051 --> 00:26:58,512
Is there anyone from Inubushi's Food Truck?

374
00:26:58,512 --> 00:27:00,522
I'm here!

375
00:27:03,100 --> 00:27:06,520
- Sorry for being late.
- That's okay.

376
00:27:06,520 --> 00:27:08,981
- Wasabi Store?
- Here.

377
00:27:08,981 --> 00:27:10,524
Eclin Store?

378
00:27:10,524 --> 00:27:11,608
- Present.
- Thank you.

379
00:27:11,608 --> 00:27:13,527
All right. Let's get to work.

380
00:27:13,527 --> 00:27:14,862
Can you get this as well?

381
00:27:14,862 --> 00:27:16,496
Over here.

382
00:27:32,421 --> 00:27:34,055
Oh, that's cold!

383
00:27:50,522 --> 00:27:53,192
- Hong.
- What's up, Rock?

384
00:27:53,192 --> 00:27:55,277
You promised only to call in emergencies.

385
00:27:55,277 --> 00:27:57,154
It's actually an emergency right now.

386
00:27:57,154 --> 00:27:58,955
<i>Hong!</i>

387
00:28:01,033 --> 00:28:02,326
What's wrong with you?

388
00:28:02,326 --> 00:28:04,745
You said you were going to Jeju Island.
What on earth are you doing in Japan?

389
00:28:04,745 --> 00:28:06,705
It's pretty much the same.

390
00:28:06,705 --> 00:28:09,473
It's about as close as Jeju,
and Japan's an island, too.

391
00:28:09,473 --> 00:28:11,293
Come back home right now.

392
00:28:11,293 --> 00:28:14,296
If you're done with college,
you should be thinking about working

393
00:28:14,296 --> 00:28:16,382
instead of running away
like an adolescent child!

394
00:28:16,382 --> 00:28:18,725
Yeah, I'm not a child anymore,
so I moved out.

395
00:28:20,010 --> 00:28:22,846
Are you listening to yourself right now?

396
00:28:22,846 --> 00:28:25,766
Stop wasting your time and come back home,

397
00:28:25,766 --> 00:28:27,434
<i>or you'll regret all this later!</i>

398
00:28:27,434 --> 00:28:28,519
Listen, Mom.

399
00:28:28,519 --> 00:28:31,021
It's up to me whether I decide
to waste my time or not.

400
00:28:31,021 --> 00:28:32,231
It's my life.

401
00:28:32,231 --> 00:28:36,068
You don't even know why I came here
and what it is that I want to do, do you?

402
00:28:36,068 --> 00:28:38,779
You're always the same.
You dip your toes in this and that,

403
00:28:38,779 --> 00:28:41,156
<i>then quit when things don't work out.</i>

404
00:28:41,156 --> 00:28:44,702
I know you ran away
because you're afraid to get a job.

405
00:28:44,702 --> 00:28:46,662
- Mom!
<i>- What?</i>

406
00:28:46,662 --> 00:28:49,047
<i>Am I wrong?</i>

407
00:28:49,915 --> 00:28:51,500
No, you're right.

408
00:28:51,500 --> 00:28:54,336
I did run away.

409
00:28:54,336 --> 00:28:56,095
I ran away from you.

410
00:29:13,564 --> 00:29:15,990
Talk about perfect timing.

411
00:29:48,265 --> 00:29:50,024
I was wondering...

412
00:29:52,436 --> 00:29:57,323
If you're free after work tonight...

413
00:30:01,612 --> 00:30:04,038
do you want to go for a drink?

414
00:30:18,712 --> 00:30:20,847
I see.

415
00:30:21,882 --> 00:30:25,886
So, you might end up staying
in Japan for a while then.

416
00:30:25,886 --> 00:30:29,306
I'm not sure yet.

417
00:30:29,306 --> 00:30:32,650
I'm trying to get ready
to go to graduate school...

418
00:30:33,811 --> 00:30:36,730
but I don't know if I should stay here

419
00:30:36,730 --> 00:30:39,274
or just move on.

420
00:30:39,274 --> 00:30:42,035
I'm not even sure if I'll like it here.

421
00:30:44,196 --> 00:30:48,742
You should take your time
and think about it while you're here.

422
00:30:48,742 --> 00:30:50,369
That's all I want.

423
00:30:50,369 --> 00:30:53,163
I want to mull it over and take things slow.

424
00:30:53,163 --> 00:30:55,590
But you know,

425
00:30:56,333 --> 00:30:59,677
life sometimes needs time to buffer.

426
00:31:00,379 --> 00:31:02,138
"Buffer"?

427
00:31:02,798 --> 00:31:04,883
I mean,

428
00:31:04,883 --> 00:31:08,303
it's kind of like putting on the brakes.

429
00:31:08,303 --> 00:31:12,398
I see what you mean.
Like brakes that slow you down?

430
00:31:18,731 --> 00:31:21,775
The person who's meant to be on my side

431
00:31:21,775 --> 00:31:25,696
can't seem to understand me.

432
00:31:25,696 --> 00:31:28,540
They don't even seem to want to try.

433
00:31:29,408 --> 00:31:32,001
Has that ever happened to you?

434
00:31:38,542 --> 00:31:41,628
It happens sometimes.

435
00:31:41,628 --> 00:31:44,256
And it hurts so much when it does.

436
00:31:44,256 --> 00:31:46,091
It's so frustrating.

437
00:31:46,091 --> 00:31:48,643
Why else would I come all the way here?

438
00:31:52,890 --> 00:31:55,434
Oh, by the way.

439
00:31:55,434 --> 00:31:58,062
You're a literature major, right?

440
00:31:58,062 --> 00:32:00,939
- Right.
- So am I!

441
00:32:00,939 --> 00:32:02,615
No way!

442
00:32:04,234 --> 00:32:07,488
We have quite a lot in common.

443
00:32:07,488 --> 00:32:09,615
How so?

444
00:32:09,615 --> 00:32:13,243
Well, we both have the same major,

445
00:32:13,243 --> 00:32:15,788
and we're both desperate for work.

446
00:32:15,788 --> 00:32:17,206
And...

447
00:32:17,206 --> 00:32:19,090
What else...

448
00:32:20,250 --> 00:32:21,418
Right!

449
00:32:21,418 --> 00:32:23,428
We're both buffering!

450
00:32:24,129 --> 00:32:26,014
You're right.

451
00:32:30,761 --> 00:32:34,314
So, why did you choose literature?

452
00:32:37,893 --> 00:32:41,855
I wanted to become a writer.

453
00:32:41,855 --> 00:32:45,665
Actually, I feel more comfortable

454
00:32:45,665 --> 00:32:48,217
expressing my thoughts on paper.

455
00:32:49,488 --> 00:32:52,415
What are you writing these days?

456
00:32:53,300 --> 00:32:56,370
Well, just this and that.

457
00:32:56,370 --> 00:33:00,290
I just write down whatever comes to mind,

458
00:33:00,290 --> 00:33:03,885
but it's nothing to write home about.

459
00:33:10,217 --> 00:33:12,386
I think you'll make it.

460
00:33:12,386 --> 00:33:14,263
Pardon?

461
00:33:14,263 --> 00:33:16,105
As a writer, I mean.

462
00:33:18,434 --> 00:33:20,276
You think so?

463
00:33:20,936 --> 00:33:22,779
Trust me.

464
00:33:24,690 --> 00:33:26,407
I just have a feeling.

465
00:33:33,323 --> 00:33:35,041
Can I...

466
00:33:36,160 --> 00:33:38,203
really trust your feelings?

467
00:33:38,203 --> 00:33:39,811
If you don't believe me,

468
00:33:39,811 --> 00:33:42,458
then come and see for yourself.

469
00:33:42,458 --> 00:33:44,133
What?

470
00:33:50,883 --> 00:33:52,517
Come on.

471
00:34:00,684 --> 00:34:02,227
Let's go!

472
00:34:02,227 --> 00:34:03,903
You've got this.

473
00:34:09,568 --> 00:34:11,953
Come on, Bonobono!

474
00:34:12,696 --> 00:34:14,664
That's it. You got it!

475
00:34:30,047 --> 00:34:31,423
That's too bad.

476
00:34:31,423 --> 00:34:34,934
I was hoping it'd be a Bonobono.

477
00:34:36,303 --> 00:34:38,180
So, if you got Dai Nee-chan,

478
00:34:38,180 --> 00:34:41,433
does that mean your feelings were off?

479
00:34:41,433 --> 00:34:43,936
You know about Dai Nee-chan?

480
00:34:43,936 --> 00:34:47,648
Not many people know about that character.

481
00:34:47,648 --> 00:34:51,610
She's the older sister of Shimarisu-kun,
who is Bonobono's friend.

482
00:34:51,610 --> 00:34:53,487
Oh, no way!

483
00:34:53,487 --> 00:34:55,622
You really do know her!

484
00:34:56,365 --> 00:35:00,803
Shall we call it a day?
It looks like you're fresh out of luck.

485
00:35:00,803 --> 00:35:03,372
Did you say we're going for another drink?

486
00:35:03,372 --> 00:35:05,874
What? You seem pretty drunk already.

487
00:35:05,874 --> 00:35:07,543
I'm totally fine.

488
00:35:07,543 --> 00:35:10,462
I haven't even had that much to drink.

489
00:35:10,462 --> 00:35:13,674
You had ten lemon sours.

490
00:35:13,674 --> 00:35:15,816
Hey, this is Choi Hong you're talking to.

491
00:35:15,816 --> 00:35:17,344
What was that?

492
00:35:17,344 --> 00:35:18,804
Choi?

493
00:35:18,804 --> 00:35:21,557
That's right. Choi Hong.

494
00:35:21,557 --> 00:35:23,289
My last name is Choi,

495
00:35:23,289 --> 00:35:25,591
and my first name is Hong.

496
00:35:28,605 --> 00:35:30,315
I'm Jungo.

497
00:35:30,315 --> 00:35:32,742
My name's Aoki Jungo.

498
00:35:33,527 --> 00:35:35,571
- Jungo.
- Right.

499
00:35:35,571 --> 00:35:37,330
Jungo...

500
00:35:38,657 --> 00:35:40,834
Hey, Jungo.

501
00:35:43,287 --> 00:35:46,999
Doesn't Dai Nee-chan look lonely to you?

502
00:35:46,999 --> 00:35:48,432
You know what we should do?

503
00:35:48,432 --> 00:35:51,462
We should look for her boyfriend!

504
00:35:51,462 --> 00:35:53,756
- Are you talking about Pippo?
- That's right!

505
00:35:53,756 --> 00:35:57,342
We need to find Pippo
so they can be with each other!

506
00:35:57,342 --> 00:35:59,644
- All right, then.
- Good.

507
00:36:06,825 --> 00:36:09,396
Come on, Pippo!

508
00:36:09,396 --> 00:36:11,440
You got one again!

509
00:36:11,440 --> 00:36:13,074
That's amazing!

510
00:36:25,871 --> 00:36:27,206
What's the matter?

511
00:36:27,206 --> 00:36:31,627
I could've got Pippo
if I just played one more round.

512
00:36:31,627 --> 00:36:36,507
Dai Nee-chan needs to have Pippo by her side.

513
00:36:36,507 --> 00:36:39,343
You've got nothing to worry about.

514
00:36:39,343 --> 00:36:41,470
Even if it wasn't for you,

515
00:36:41,470 --> 00:36:44,348
they'll always have each other.

516
00:36:44,348 --> 00:36:46,316
Their love is everlasting.

517
00:36:48,102 --> 00:36:50,153
Everlasting...

518
00:36:55,984 --> 00:36:59,704
Do you believe in everlasting love?

519
00:37:03,033 --> 00:37:06,836
That's a difficult question.

520
00:37:10,165 --> 00:37:14,427
I mean, it has to exist somewhere, right?

521
00:37:18,132 --> 00:37:20,308
"Somewhere"?

522
00:37:23,595 --> 00:37:25,271
I made up my mind!

523
00:37:26,724 --> 00:37:30,269
I'm going to stay here.

524
00:37:30,269 --> 00:37:33,905
I want to go and see where that "somewhere" is.

525
00:37:37,901 --> 00:37:39,570
By the way,

526
00:37:39,570 --> 00:37:41,989
where do you live?

527
00:37:41,989 --> 00:37:43,782
Don't worry about me.

528
00:37:43,782 --> 00:37:46,042
I can get home by myself.

529
00:37:46,994 --> 00:37:48,996
Goodbye.

530
00:37:48,996 --> 00:37:50,998
How are you going to get home?

531
00:37:50,998 --> 00:37:53,375
I'm going to run.

532
00:37:53,375 --> 00:37:55,176
In this rain?

533
00:37:56,518 --> 00:37:58,505
Don't worry.

534
00:37:58,505 --> 00:38:03,268
I'm probably much faster than you.

535
00:38:10,851 --> 00:38:12,144
You might

536
00:38:12,144 --> 00:38:14,496
have me fooled for a weakling,

537
00:38:14,496 --> 00:38:16,832
but I actually run
around Inokashira Park every morning.

538
00:38:16,832 --> 00:38:19,550
I do five laps each day.

539
00:38:20,877 --> 00:38:23,714
There's no way
you can run five laps every day.

540
00:38:23,714 --> 00:38:26,258
Hold on. You don't believe me?

541
00:38:26,258 --> 00:38:27,926
Of course not.

542
00:38:27,926 --> 00:38:31,305
Do you have any idea
how big Inokashira Park is?

543
00:38:31,305 --> 00:38:33,140
Unbelievable.

544
00:38:33,140 --> 00:38:35,392
I'm being serious!

545
00:38:35,392 --> 00:38:37,394
Do you want me to show you?

546
00:38:37,394 --> 00:38:39,604
You'll kick yourself.

547
00:38:39,604 --> 00:38:41,989
Don't you dare take your eyes off me.

548
00:38:44,568 --> 00:38:46,778
Wait! You're way too drunk.

549
00:38:46,778 --> 00:38:47,904
Hong?

550
00:38:47,904 --> 00:38:49,622
Hong!

551
00:38:54,703 --> 00:38:58,714
She's actually pretty good.

552
00:39:11,762 --> 00:39:14,014
Well, look who it is.

553
00:39:14,014 --> 00:39:16,190
If it isn't the resident lunatic.

554
00:39:19,186 --> 00:39:20,520
So, tell me.

555
00:39:20,520 --> 00:39:22,989
How much did you have to drink?

556
00:39:26,902 --> 00:39:29,279
That's weird.

557
00:39:29,279 --> 00:39:31,782
Did I bump my head somewhere?

558
00:39:31,782 --> 00:39:33,624
Just have some breakfast.

559
00:39:35,285 --> 00:39:36,411
So?

560
00:39:36,411 --> 00:39:37,829
What was he like?

561
00:39:37,829 --> 00:39:39,373
You met him, didn't you?

562
00:39:39,373 --> 00:39:41,090
The hotdog man?

563
00:39:41,708 --> 00:39:43,835
Yes.

564
00:39:43,835 --> 00:39:45,462
I did.

565
00:39:45,462 --> 00:39:47,506
And?

566
00:39:47,506 --> 00:39:49,182
Well...

567
00:39:56,223 --> 00:39:57,940
Give me money.

568
00:40:24,835 --> 00:40:27,796
I'm so proud of you, Hong.

569
00:40:27,796 --> 00:40:29,430
Me too...

570
00:40:31,258 --> 00:40:33,844
Hey, don't worry about it too much.

571
00:40:33,844 --> 00:40:36,395
You'll see him again
if you two are meant to be.

572
00:40:38,473 --> 00:40:40,733
I doubt it.

573
00:41:00,037 --> 00:41:03,832
<i>I've never believed in such things.</i>

574
00:41:03,832 --> 00:41:06,126
<i>Rather than believing in fate or miracles,</i>

575
00:41:06,126 --> 00:41:10,346
<i>I've always wanted to have faith in myself.</i>

576
00:41:11,423 --> 00:41:15,802
<i>Ji Hui thinks it's fate</i>
<i>when coincidences repeat,</i>

577
00:41:15,802 --> 00:41:17,888
<i>but I think that's just wishful thinking.</i>

578
00:41:17,888 --> 00:41:21,308
<i>People who believe in fate</i>

579
00:41:21,308 --> 00:41:23,943
<i>are the ones who hope</i>
<i>for a miracle to happen.</i>

580
00:41:25,062 --> 00:41:26,821
<i>But...</i>

581
00:41:40,494 --> 00:41:42,128
Hey.

582
00:41:46,541 --> 00:41:48,377
Wait! Hong?

583
00:41:48,377 --> 00:41:50,887
Stop!

584
00:41:51,922 --> 00:41:53,382
Wait up! Don't go!

585
00:41:53,382 --> 00:41:55,266
Hong!

586
00:41:58,887 --> 00:42:00,646
Oh, no.

587
00:42:04,101 --> 00:42:06,152
Are you all right?

588
00:42:14,361 --> 00:42:16,863
No, I'm not.

589
00:42:16,863 --> 00:42:20,082
That really hurts.

590
00:42:22,327 --> 00:42:25,213
I'm so sorry about the other night.

591
00:42:26,290 --> 00:42:28,049
Don't worry about it.

592
00:42:29,543 --> 00:42:33,714
You're a little later than usual today.

593
00:42:33,714 --> 00:42:36,300
It's already past 11 a.m.

594
00:42:36,300 --> 00:42:38,260
What?

595
00:42:38,260 --> 00:42:39,977
Have you been...

596
00:42:40,762 --> 00:42:42,597
Thanks to you,

597
00:42:42,597 --> 00:42:45,844
I'm late for school today.

598
00:42:45,844 --> 00:42:49,855
Have you been waiting for me all morning?

599
00:42:54,735 --> 00:42:55,944
I did it.

600
00:42:55,944 --> 00:42:57,662
I finally got it.

601
00:43:01,950 --> 00:43:03,827
Is this...

602
00:43:03,827 --> 00:43:06,246
When did you get this?

603
00:43:06,246 --> 00:43:10,417
Well, I happened to be in the area yesterday.

604
00:43:10,417 --> 00:43:13,712
So, I just gave it a shot,

605
00:43:13,712 --> 00:43:16,764
and this was the first one that came out.

606
00:43:24,681 --> 00:43:26,357
Please be it.

607
00:43:33,440 --> 00:43:37,493
Yes!

608
00:43:41,156 --> 00:43:43,374
About time!

609
00:43:59,925 --> 00:44:03,561
<i>That was the moment when I realized</i>

610
00:44:04,429 --> 00:44:06,848
<i>that fate</i>

611
00:44:06,848 --> 00:44:09,017
<i>really did exist</i>

612
00:44:09,017 --> 00:44:11,110
<i>in this world.</i>

613
00:44:15,273 --> 00:44:19,903
<i>I never felt anything like it before.</i>

614
00:44:19,903 --> 00:44:23,490
<i>It was also a moment</i>

615
00:44:23,490 --> 00:44:25,666
<i>that I would never get to experience again.</i>

616
00:44:28,787 --> 00:44:30,872
<i>Please hand in your work by next week.</i>

617
00:44:30,872 --> 00:44:32,624
All right. That's it for today.

618
00:44:32,624 --> 00:44:34,884
Well done, everyone.

619
00:44:35,669 --> 00:44:39,555
Please come and ask me
if you have any questions.

620
00:44:46,013 --> 00:44:48,022
Jungo!

621
00:45:01,903 --> 00:45:03,955
A cherry blossom.

622
00:45:18,545 --> 00:45:20,805
[CLOSED]

623
00:45:22,883 --> 00:45:26,053
- I'll see you tomorrow, everyone.
- See you!

624
00:45:26,053 --> 00:45:29,014
Hold on. You look much happier than usual.

625
00:45:29,014 --> 00:45:30,390
- What?
- That look on your face...

626
00:45:30,390 --> 00:45:32,233
What are you talking about?

627
00:45:39,441 --> 00:45:40,859
I knew it, Hong!

628
00:45:40,859 --> 00:45:42,527
You finally scored!

629
00:45:42,527 --> 00:45:44,871
Stop it, you guys!

630
00:45:46,615 --> 00:45:48,458
I'll see you tomorrow!

631
00:45:49,660 --> 00:45:52,503
- Bye!
- Have fun!

632
00:45:53,580 --> 00:45:55,332
They look so good together.

633
00:45:55,332 --> 00:45:57,793
She's got some moves.

634
00:45:57,793 --> 00:45:59,844
It must be young love!

635
00:46:28,699 --> 00:46:30,958
It's so beautiful.

636
00:46:32,077 --> 00:46:36,047
How do I say "beautiful" in Korean?

637
00:46:36,999 --> 00:46:39,668
It's a bit hard to pronounce.

638
00:46:39,668 --> 00:46:41,928
You have to say, "<i>yeppeuda.</i>"

639
00:46:42,546 --> 00:46:44,555
<i>Yeppeuda.</i>

640
00:46:45,382 --> 00:46:47,467
That was pretty good!

641
00:46:47,467 --> 00:46:49,477
So, it's <i>yeppeuda.</i>

642
00:46:56,685 --> 00:46:58,736
<i>Yeppeuda.</i>

643
00:47:10,532 --> 00:47:12,166
Hong.

644
00:47:45,984 --> 00:47:47,618
Sorry.

645
00:48:00,958 --> 00:48:03,217
<i>That spring was...</i>

646
00:48:03,794 --> 00:48:06,380
<i>the beginning...</i>

647
00:48:06,380 --> 00:48:08,639
<i>and end of my spring symphony.</i>

648
00:48:14,388 --> 00:48:16,223
<i>Back then,</i>

649
00:48:16,223 --> 00:48:18,600
<i>I firmly believed</i>
<i>that if I truly loved someone...</i>

650
00:48:18,600 --> 00:48:20,394
[SEOUL, 5 YEARS LATER]

651
00:48:20,394 --> 00:48:24,530
<i>...the abundance of the universe</i>
<i>would be there to help me.</i>

652
00:48:25,524 --> 00:48:27,450
<i>That was what I believed.</i>

653
00:48:30,946 --> 00:48:33,790
<i>Everyone knows</i>

654
00:48:34,658 --> 00:48:37,585
<i>that love has an expiry date.</i>

655
00:48:41,498 --> 00:48:43,716
<i>But I believed</i>

656
00:48:44,418 --> 00:48:47,254
<i>things would be different for me.</i>

657
00:48:47,254 --> 00:48:49,430
<i>I believed our love would be different.</i>

658
00:48:54,261 --> 00:48:58,056
<i>After I broke up with Jungo</i>
<i>and came back from Japan,</i>

659
00:48:58,056 --> 00:49:00,399
<i>I was tormented by the fear</i>

660
00:49:01,435 --> 00:49:04,229
<i>that I would end up destroying myself</i>

661
00:49:04,229 --> 00:49:07,024
<i>if I didn't immerse myself in something.</i>

662
00:49:07,024 --> 00:49:09,026
[SODAM BOOKS]

663
00:49:09,026 --> 00:49:11,570
I've made some notes on it.

664
00:49:11,570 --> 00:49:13,704
Would you like to take a look?

665
00:49:14,990 --> 00:49:17,492
Mr. Lee, this is the final version.

666
00:49:17,492 --> 00:49:19,453
Okay.

667
00:49:19,453 --> 00:49:20,912
Ms. Choi.

668
00:49:20,912 --> 00:49:22,581
This is the final version.

669
00:49:22,581 --> 00:49:25,459
We'll go ahead and print it
if you don't find any issues.

670
00:49:25,459 --> 00:49:27,044
Could you take a look?

671
00:49:27,044 --> 00:49:28,920
I'll get back to you after one last read.

672
00:49:28,920 --> 00:49:30,763
Sure.

673
00:50:10,754 --> 00:50:13,681
<i>If I knew that</i>
<i>I was going to meet Jungo...</i>

674
00:50:15,550 --> 00:50:17,894
<i>I wouldn't have gone.</i>

675
00:50:23,266 --> 00:50:24,643
Ms. Choi.

676
00:50:24,643 --> 00:50:27,604
- Did you see the snow outside?
- I did.

677
00:50:27,604 --> 00:50:30,357
I was stuck in traffic because of it.

678
00:50:30,357 --> 00:50:32,067
Right.

679
00:50:32,067 --> 00:50:34,653
If everyone is here,
let's get on with it, shall we?

680
00:50:34,653 --> 00:50:36,196
Yes, ma'am.

681
00:50:36,196 --> 00:50:39,491
First, let me show you
the cover design for the reprint.

682
00:50:39,491 --> 00:50:41,535
We've already seen it last time.

683
00:50:41,535 --> 00:50:43,412
Let's move on to the next agenda.

684
00:50:43,412 --> 00:50:44,871
Yes, ma'am.

685
00:50:44,871 --> 00:50:48,792
We couldn't decide on the copy
for the cover in our last meeting.

686
00:50:48,792 --> 00:50:51,169
I've narrowed it down to these two options.

687
00:50:51,169 --> 00:50:53,130
Let me read them to you first.

688
00:50:53,130 --> 00:50:56,641
That's fine. Let's just read it ourselves.

689
00:50:59,928 --> 00:51:02,556
Have we still not received
Ms. Park Ji Hui's manuscript?

690
00:51:02,556 --> 00:51:07,026
Well, we haven't been able
to get a hold of her since yesterday.

691
00:51:08,687 --> 00:51:10,105
All right.

692
00:51:10,105 --> 00:51:12,149
I'll try to get in touch with her.

693
00:51:12,149 --> 00:51:14,774
Mr. Lee, are you ready for next week's event?

694
00:51:14,774 --> 00:51:15,909
Yes, Ms. Choi.

695
00:51:15,909 --> 00:51:18,989
Mr. Sasae will get here
by lunchtime tomorrow as scheduled.

696
00:51:18,989 --> 00:51:23,118
Once he arrives, the interview will proceed at 4 p.m.

697
00:51:23,118 --> 00:51:27,495
Mr. Lee, can you keep working
with the CEO on the Japanese section?

698
00:51:27,495 --> 00:51:29,541
I know you're busy
with the South American section.

699
00:51:29,541 --> 00:51:31,168
Don't worry about us.

700
00:51:31,168 --> 00:51:33,636
Everything's going to be perfect.

701
00:51:36,298 --> 00:51:40,260
Sir, can we make the color a bit darker?

702
00:51:40,260 --> 00:51:42,562
Of course, we can.

703
00:51:44,890 --> 00:51:45,974
This way.

704
00:51:45,974 --> 00:51:49,819
- Have we received the first shipment?
- Yes, it's all here.

705
00:51:51,563 --> 00:51:53,732
And the second batch
is arriving in two days, right?

706
00:51:53,732 --> 00:51:55,867
Yes, it'll all get here in time.

707
00:52:14,252 --> 00:52:15,970
When did you get here?

708
00:52:17,506 --> 00:52:19,308
Just now.

709
00:52:19,308 --> 00:52:20,984
What's that?

710
00:52:23,270 --> 00:52:24,905
It's a cake.

711
00:52:25,606 --> 00:52:27,483
I was craving for something sweet.

712
00:52:27,483 --> 00:52:29,235
How did you know?

713
00:52:29,235 --> 00:52:32,704
How do you always know me so well?

714
00:52:33,881 --> 00:52:36,633
It's nice to hear
such a lovely compliment,

715
00:52:36,633 --> 00:52:39,887
but it feels like
you're happier to see this than me.

716
00:52:39,887 --> 00:52:41,263
How did you know?

717
00:52:41,263 --> 00:52:43,565
See? I'm an open book to you.

718
00:52:46,226 --> 00:52:47,311
Hold on.

719
00:52:47,311 --> 00:52:49,271
You didn't forget
what day today is, did you?

720
00:52:49,271 --> 00:52:50,814
Today?

721
00:52:50,814 --> 00:52:53,192
Is it Valentine's Day? No, it's not.

722
00:52:53,192 --> 00:52:54,951
No way.

723
00:52:56,070 --> 00:52:58,030
Is it Cake Day?

724
00:52:58,030 --> 00:53:00,949
It's your mother's birthday today.

725
00:53:00,949 --> 00:53:04,036
You're right! What time is it now?

726
00:53:04,036 --> 00:53:06,705
Come on, Hong.

727
00:53:06,705 --> 00:53:08,082
Didn't you forget last year as well?

728
00:53:08,082 --> 00:53:10,226
But lunar birthdays are so confusing.

729
00:53:10,226 --> 00:53:12,853
I forgot to get her something.

730
00:53:12,853 --> 00:53:14,421
Let's just go.

731
00:53:14,421 --> 00:53:16,472
What? Okay.

732
00:53:18,217 --> 00:53:19,885
Min Jun.

733
00:53:19,885 --> 00:53:22,179
Can we tell her that this is from me?

734
00:53:22,179 --> 00:53:23,889
Please?

735
00:53:23,889 --> 00:53:27,351
Don't give me that look.
You can't win me over that easily.

736
00:53:27,351 --> 00:53:30,037
Please, Min Jun. Can we?

737
00:53:30,037 --> 00:53:33,464
Just this once. Please.

738
00:53:37,753 --> 00:53:39,755
Did Jun say he'll be here by 7 p.m.?

739
00:53:39,755 --> 00:53:41,006
Yes, he did.

740
00:53:41,006 --> 00:53:42,633
I told you he would be.

741
00:53:42,633 --> 00:53:44,885
Why do you have to keep checking?

742
00:53:44,885 --> 00:53:48,263
You should've picked him up yourself.

743
00:53:48,263 --> 00:53:50,223
What's with the attitude?

744
00:53:50,223 --> 00:53:52,900
I just want to make sure there's enough food.

745
00:53:53,810 --> 00:53:57,606
If I ever get a boyfriend,
I'm never going to tell you.

746
00:53:57,606 --> 00:54:00,074
Sure. Don't bother.

747
00:54:01,151 --> 00:54:02,869
That must be them.

748
00:54:04,404 --> 00:54:05,781
Hello, my brother-in-law-to-be.

749
00:54:05,781 --> 00:54:07,908
Hey. How have you been?

750
00:54:07,908 --> 00:54:10,619
"Brother-in-law"? That's so weird.

751
00:54:10,619 --> 00:54:13,786
Hey, let her be.
She's just practicing. Right?

752
00:54:13,786 --> 00:54:15,165
Hello, Jun.

753
00:54:15,165 --> 00:54:16,208
Come on in.

754
00:54:16,208 --> 00:54:19,002
Happy birthday, Mother.

755
00:54:19,002 --> 00:54:22,297
Thanks, Min Jun. You must be hungry.

756
00:54:22,297 --> 00:54:25,634
This makes me so happy.

757
00:54:25,634 --> 00:54:28,762
This is such a lovely cake!

758
00:54:28,762 --> 00:54:31,682
Didn't you hate birthdays
because it made you feel old?

759
00:54:31,682 --> 00:54:32,746
What's gotten into you?

760
00:54:32,746 --> 00:54:35,102
I'm celebrating with my future son-in-law.

761
00:54:35,102 --> 00:54:39,106
You have no idea how happy I am.

762
00:54:39,106 --> 00:54:42,567
Just wait until you meet yours later.
You'll know exactly how I feel.

763
00:54:42,567 --> 00:54:44,569
Can you stop getting ahead of yourself?

764
00:54:44,569 --> 00:54:46,238
Why are you and Rock being so weird?

765
00:54:46,238 --> 00:54:49,992
No, you're being weird.
We're basically a family now.

766
00:54:49,992 --> 00:54:51,667
That's right.

767
00:54:52,786 --> 00:54:54,037
I'm so sorry.

768
00:54:54,037 --> 00:54:55,956
I had to take this call.

769
00:54:55,956 --> 00:54:58,083
So, what did I miss?

770
00:54:58,083 --> 00:55:01,920
Don't worry.
You didn't miss anything important.

771
00:55:01,920 --> 00:55:03,255
By the way, Hong.

772
00:55:03,255 --> 00:55:06,466
- Can I ask you for a favor?
- A favor?

773
00:55:06,466 --> 00:55:08,593
Can you go to the airport for me tomorrow?

774
00:55:08,593 --> 00:55:11,346
- What?
- I need a replacement interpreter

775
00:55:11,346 --> 00:55:14,725
because Ms. Miyazawa had
something urgent come up at home.

776
00:55:14,725 --> 00:55:16,818
You want me to interpret?

777
00:55:17,978 --> 00:55:20,272
Come on, Dad. I can't.

778
00:55:20,272 --> 00:55:23,775
It's been years since I last spoke Japanese.

779
00:55:23,775 --> 00:55:25,444
Why can't you go instead?

780
00:55:25,444 --> 00:55:27,276
You're good at Japanese, too.

781
00:55:27,276 --> 00:55:29,824
Dad's going to Busan for work tomorrow.

782
00:55:30,615 --> 00:55:33,493
I just need you to cover for tomorrow.

783
00:55:33,493 --> 00:55:36,371
I already made plans
with Min Jun tomorrow.

784
00:55:36,371 --> 00:55:38,790
Don't worry. You should go.

785
00:55:38,790 --> 00:55:40,842
He needs your help.

786
00:55:42,044 --> 00:55:43,678
Okay?

787
00:55:46,840 --> 00:55:48,550
That's my son-in-law.

788
00:55:48,550 --> 00:55:50,385
- Help yourselves.
- Thank you.

789
00:55:50,385 --> 00:55:53,020
- Thank you.
- Thanks, Mom.

790
00:55:57,643 --> 00:55:58,977
I'm sorry.

791
00:55:58,977 --> 00:56:02,064
We'll have to check
on the venues next week.

792
00:56:02,064 --> 00:56:03,482
It's okay. I understand.

793
00:56:03,482 --> 00:56:07,319
I'll look for a few more places
for us to check out next week.

794
00:56:07,319 --> 00:56:08,953
Okay.

795
00:56:14,457 --> 00:56:16,091
Min Jun.

796
00:56:16,787 --> 00:56:18,664
Yes?

797
00:56:18,664 --> 00:56:20,832
Thank you.

798
00:56:20,832 --> 00:56:23,666
Oh, come on.
I told you not to say that.

799
00:56:23,666 --> 00:56:25,724
Whenever you say that,

800
00:56:25,724 --> 00:56:28,276
you sound so distant.

801
00:56:29,841 --> 00:56:31,517
Good night.

802
00:56:33,929 --> 00:56:35,813
Go inside. It's cold.

803
00:56:53,281 --> 00:56:55,492
You're a lifesaver, Ms. Choi.

804
00:56:55,492 --> 00:56:58,161
I didn't realize you knew Japanese.

805
00:56:58,161 --> 00:56:59,705
Did you study there?

806
00:56:59,705 --> 00:57:03,758
No, I lived there for a bit when I was little.

807
00:57:04,626 --> 00:57:08,213
I took classes for a year
and got pretty good grades,

808
00:57:08,213 --> 00:57:10,424
but I get nervous when it really matters.

809
00:57:10,424 --> 00:57:12,308
I still get stage fright.

810
00:57:14,720 --> 00:57:17,139
He'll be here soon. Shall we?

811
00:57:17,139 --> 00:57:18,856
Right, of course.

812
00:57:28,608 --> 00:57:31,953
[WELCOME, MR. SASAE HIKARI]

813
00:57:32,779 --> 00:57:34,781
I didn't expect him to be so late.

814
00:57:34,781 --> 00:57:36,541
Where is he?

815
00:57:41,204 --> 00:57:43,047
Yes, Mr. Park.

816
00:57:44,082 --> 00:57:46,501
I'm at the airport.

817
00:57:46,501 --> 00:57:49,303
- Excuse me, Ms. Choi.
- Sure.

818
00:58:52,856 --> 00:58:54,987
<i>Time stood still...</i>

819
00:58:54,987 --> 00:58:58,373
<i>like a neatly folded piece of paper.</i>

820
00:59:02,869 --> 00:59:05,797
<i>If I knew that I was going to meet Jungo...</i>

821
00:59:07,582 --> 00:59:10,009
<i>I would have never come.</i>
